2.)	Pointer Management

Describe the problem with this function: 
void foo() 
{ 
	  	int *array = new int[100]; 
      for(int i = 0; i < 100; i++) 
      { 
      /// Do something; 
      } 
} 

- The function has a problem because it allocates memory but does not release it afterward.
When "new int[100]" is used, it creates space in memory for 100 integers. But, the function 
ends without using "delete[]" to free that allocated memory. Once the function finishes, the
pointer array goes out of scope, so the program loses access to the address of that memory. 
Even though the pointer disappears, the memory is still reserved in the system. 

This situation leads to a memory leak, and if the function is called many times, the program 
will continue using more and more memory unnecessarily.
